<validation>
1. Demonstrate CSWSH by opening WebSocket from attacker origin
2. Show authentication bypass or token theft
3. Prove message injection (SQL, XSS, command injection)
4. Document origin validation bypass technique
5. Show message tampering (impersonation, privilege escalation)
6. Provide working proof-of-concept HTML page
7. Include WebSocket message logs showing exploitation
</validation>

<false_positives>
- WebSocket requires CSRF token in handshake
- Token-based auth (not cookies) with proper validation
- Strong origin validation with no bypass
- Message integrity checks (HMAC, signatures)
- Per-message authorization
- Rate limiting enforced
- Input validation on all message fields
</false_positives>

<impact>
- Cross-Site WebSocket Hijacking (CSWSH)
- Authentication bypass
- Session hijacking
- Data exfiltration
- Message injection and tampering
- User impersonation
- Remote code execution via injection
- Denial of service
</impact>

<pro_tips>
1. Always test for CSWSH if cookies are used
2. Origin header is easily spoofed—must be validated server-side
3. Check if auth token sent in URL (logged, cached)
4. Test message handlers for all injection types
5. Replay captured messages—check for nonce/timestamp validation
6. Try injecting privileged fields in messages
7. WebSocket security often overlooked compared to HTTP
8. Test both handshake and message-level authentication
9. Check if messages validated on every send or just at connection
10. Use Burp/ZAP to intercept and modify live messages
11. Browser DevTools excellent for monitoring WebSocket traffic
12. ws:// (unencrypted) should never be used in production
13. Mixed content (ws:// from https://page) often allowed by browsers
14. Protocol upgrade phase is complex—potential for smuggling
15. Test all message types—authorization may be inconsistent
</pro_tips>

<remember>WebSocket security is fundamentally different from HTTP. Persistent connections bypass many traditional security controls. CSWSH is the WebSocket equivalent of CSRF. Cookie-based authentication without additional protection is almost always vulnerable. Origin validation must be rigorous and server-side. Every message type needs separate authentication and authorization checks. Message tampering and injection are high-value attacks. Test WebSocket as thoroughly as you test HTTP APIs.</remember>
</websocket_hijacking_guide>
